Inflation in Europe jumped due to food
The accelerating inflation measured in the Eurozone is mainly caused by the constant rise in food prices.
November price growth in the 13 countries of the eurozone was higher than expected, after 2.6 percent in October, annual inflation was registered at 3.1 percent, the Luxembourg statistical office of the Union announced.
The official forecast predicted only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian banks of issue, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the key interest rate, saying that the cut, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to it.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to &quot;dissuade&quot; inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent represents a fifteen-year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the Eurozone has soared due to soaring food and energy prices.
Futures prices for wheat rose by 88 percent, and the soybean exchange rate also reached its highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets has risen by 52 percent this year, and last month one barrel of black gold already cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from this year&#39;s 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation will remain around 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup sees a government crisis
The circle of supporters of the Fidesz movement increased significantly after a long period of stagnation at the beginning of December, so it now has the largest camp since 2002, while in the case of the Socialists, the Gallup Institute has never measured such a low - 13 percent support.
In the case of certain voters of the party, the difference - due to the greater determination of the opposition voters - would represent more than two-thirds (71 percent) support compared to one-fifth of MSZP&#39;s support.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the threshold for entering parliament: their support among the entire population is two percent.
Among certain voters of the party, there are one percent more supporters of both camps.
The public&#39;s opinion of the economy has worsened even from the previous low - the proportion of those who consider the country&#39;s economic situation to be downright very bad has never been so high - 41 percent, while another 46 percent say the situation is quite bad.
Families evaluate the change in their material situation after more hopeful prospects in the spring and summer, now again more pessimistically.
As for next year, a larger part of the population expects a further deterioration and only a tenth an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, which is the most of all Gallup Institute polls to date, thought that the prime minister was doing his job poorly rather than well.
Ferenc Gyurcsány is trusted or very trusted by 13 percent of those polled, while Viktor Orbán&#39;s share of supporters is 38 percent.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all, 27 percent the leader of the Fidesz movement.
One of the indicators of the development of the political situation is how much of the public believes that dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be resolved without a change of government.
While after last October&#39;s riots, 35 percent considered the government and the prime minister to remain in place as desirable, currently this share is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) see the solution only in calling new elections.
It is significant for the interest in the referendum that 60 percent of the respondents answered the question regarding their possible participation that they would definitely take part in the referendum and another 20 percent said that they would probably take part.
By comparison, only 55 percent would definitely participate in &quot;parliamentary elections held this Sunday&quot; and another 15 percent consider their participation likely. The success of the referendum would be undoubted based on current intentions.
74 percent would say no to school fees, 79 percent to doctor&#39;s fees, and 84 percent to hospital fees.
If we look at the same shares only in the circle of people who definitely promise to participate, then the introduction of school fees, doctor&#39;s fees and hospital stay fees would be rejected by 81, 84 and 89 percent, respectively.
The most expensive is Auchan, almost a fifth more expensive than Tesco
Hypermarkets in the Budaörs business triangle maintained last year&#39;s average 16 percent increase in price levels, with the difference that there was no VAT increase this year.
Napi Gazdaság newspaper article
The usual Christmas shopping basket of Napi Gazdaság newspaper in the Budaörs business triangle increased by an average of 16 percent this year, but in all hypermarkets the price increased by well over a thousand forints.
Since the prices in supermarkets &quot;soared&quot; already last December, in percentage terms, due to the previously high basis, the price increase was not so drastic.
However, it is certainly unhappy for consumers that what they could easily buy last year for less than nine thousand forints, now they cannot even buy it for ten thousand.
The consumption basket of Daily Economy in the examined hypermarkets exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
The highest price of the basket was HUF 10,573.
(In 2003, the consumption basket cost HUF 6,800.)
The price of Unica and live fish remained almost at last year&#39;s level, but the price of wild breasts, nuts and also poppy seeds increased significantly.
The prices of bread and flour corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we found a kilogram of bread for 139 forints.
The competition did not go with the price of the product under 200 forints.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of a two-liter Coca Cola in a returnable bottle was under 200 forints, so even with the deposit, the product cost only 257 forints.
Even so, according to the consumption basket of the daily Napi Gazdaság, Auchan was the most expensive this year, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, the prices appearing in the consumer basket of the daily Napi Gazdaság increased by 15 percent compared to the prices last year at Christmas, while Tesco and Auchan increased by approximately 18 percent.
When comparing last year&#39;s highest and this year&#39;s lowest value of the consumer basket, the difference was 12 percent, while the increase between last year&#39;s lowest and this year&#39;s highest is 21 percent.
In forints, the increase was 1,480 on average.
The average price increase last year was 1,206 forints, with the fact that last Christmas the prices were affected by the increase in VAT.
It was this process that disrupted the trade, the department stores were obviously unable to decide how big a price range they should set for individual products, as they were unable to predict what effect the change in prices would have on consumption.
(If the merchant plans the circulation speed of a given product incorrectly, he can lose a significant profit due to the price spread adjusted to the intensity of circulation.)
Last year, due to VAT, the increase in the price of the Napi Gazdaság newspaper&#39;s consumer basket was so extreme that the price of the most expensive basket was HUF 1,720 higher than in 2006, while the price difference for the cheapest was HUF 844.
This year, the extreme difference did not manifest itself, the most expensive basket now cost 1,630 forints more than last year, and the cheapest also went up by 1,284 forints.
A comparison of the two Christmas seasons revealed a catastrophic rise in prices, in less than 20 months the price of daily consumption goods in hypermarkets increased by more than 30 percent.
(Among other things, this does not absolutely confirm the data of the Central Statistical Office: it measured a price increase of more than 30 percent in the case of several basic foods within 12 months.
In addition to flour, for example, also in the case of eggs.)
In the latter case, however, according to the consumption basket of the Daily Economy, it seems almost impossible, or the price level of the product, already quite expensive last year, showed a price increase of barely more than 10 percent compared to the base even in the worst case.
Flour suppliers seem to occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers, and they managed to impose a drastic price increase even in international chains.
Hypermarkets in the business golden triangle are not complaining, they are still reporting a good year.
In our experience, the majority of customers in the three stores we visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy everything in bulk, they take non-perishable food after their salaries.
On Wednesday morning, all three supermarkets had long queues at checkouts, or a sharp increase in the number of visitors.
However, as we know, turnover is lower in the countryside, several international chains complain to research companies that sales are lagging behind their plans, not only in the case of food, but also of durable consumer goods.
Many places save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to the inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overworked staff do not help stop the spread of the disease, claims the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
Many places also save on disinfectants.
A MRSA infection was recently diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John&#39;s Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who was hospitalized after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same location earlier this year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was discharged home, but not long after that he had to return with an MRSA infection, and due to the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not be performed.
Until December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multiresistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröczová, head of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that as many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been registered with certainty in hospitals, others are unknown.
Almost two-thirds (683) of the infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing illness.
Infections caused by SA (eg strep throat, tonsillitis, skin infection, morning sickness) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are given excessively or inappropriately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and that spread rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
Above all, in the case of temporary or permanent poor functioning of the immune system in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight or in elderly patients, it can cause serious hospital infections, for example morning sickness or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John&#39;s Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
&quot;An infection must not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not only there,&quot; said Tibor Nyulasi, &quot;where the presence of the pathogen is not investigated.&quot;
Resistant to antibiotics
&quot;We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treat them with rubber gloves and we have the necessary antibiotics in the mask and for their treatment,&quot; said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but even then, infection cannot always be avoided.
Taking a sample is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in domestic hospitals are not favorable for the prevention of the emergence and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, claims Karolina Böröczová.
As this infection occurs significantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen incoming patients and immediately isolate MRSA carriers.
However, the collection of microbiological samples is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations also plays a role in this.
The majority of cases are thus detected if the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment with antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, medical records.
It is necessary to strive for antibiotic therapy to be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent the emergence of resistance to drugs, but even hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
The collection of microbiological samples is even rarer in the case of basic or outpatient treatment of patients, said Karolina Böröczová.
It saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA spreads between patients most often through medical personnel.
That is why hand washing and the use of gloves and a mask play a very important role, but even in this there are serious deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and by touch, but in the conditions of domestic hospitals it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
On the contrary, the rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina Böröczová noted, unfortunately we can also encounter the fact that in hospitals that are in an unfavorable material situation, they save on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, which increases the chance of infections.
According to Karolina Böröczová, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there are demonstrably fewer similar infections or the further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its incidence.
The program appears to be a success, with MRSA infections in England showing a downward trend, according to published data.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) places the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant disease agents (which also includes MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these disease agents among its priorities.
