Another 400 million euros for infrastructure
The agreement on three credit frameworks with a total value of 400 million euros to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy was signed on Friday in Budapest by Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB).
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a framework worth EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of projects in the field of transport and the environment, implemented with the support of the Cohesion Fund, while the parties had previously concluded a loan agreement for the amount of EUR 100 million, the agreement has now been signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
A loan agreement worth 150 million euros is also used for budgetary financing of projects related to education.
The EIB has approved a total of 300 million euros for Hungary for these purposes, the remaining 150 million euros may be used later, with the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the parties signed a contract for 50 million euros, which the budget will use mainly for the research and development project of the University of Debrecen.
The 4th metro route was also discussed at the meeting.
The parties agreed that after Hungary has agreed with the EU on the details of the metro&#39;s financing, they will return to whether and how the original contract needs to be modified.
According to János Veres, this may happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary with an amount of 8.4 billion euros.
The interest on loans that the EIB provides with an eight-year waiting period and without commitment commission is tied to the EURIBOR rate.
Bulgaria is the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is astounding - the attention of the whole of Europe is turning to the previously somewhat neglected Balkan country.
What, where and who buys on the ever-cheapest, but rapidly increasing, EU market?
Analysis of Re/Max&#39;s Bulgarian division.
Bulgaria, with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses, is undoubtedly the most sought-after Eastern European property buying destination right now.
Among the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitoša, on the sea coast Albena, Golden Sands, Sunny Coast, the ancient towns of Sozobol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for real estate around Kavarna and Balčik.
According to analysts from the Re/Max Bulgaria company, sooner or later the central part of the country will attract the interest of investors as well - for example, Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - and more and more people are also buying in the vicinity of the downright cheap city of Ruse.
The capital city of Sofia also promises attractive possibilities, commercial and office spaces promise the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, becoming a sought-after travel destination in the other two seasons in addition to the summer and winter seasons.
Foresight investors are already buying in bulk, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
According to analysts, real estate buyers in Bulgaria are trying to change their life and lifestyle at the same time.
Most customers come from England, but there are also buyers from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present here, and there are traditionally many Russian customers by the Black Sea and in ski paradises.
Foreign buyers can be divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Settlers either buy renovated properties worth 50-100 thousand euros, or dilapidated old houses for 5-15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They require good accessibility and communication options, proximity to a big city, shops and usually a local doctor is important to them.
The second category is the buyers of cottages (Bulgaria ranked among the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of an increase in value in the medium or long term.
The increase in real estate prices in the capital is continuous, or the demand is getting stronger.
Real estate prices in Bulgaria are the lowest in the European Union, but they have grown by 21 percent annually over the past five years.
Rising property prices far outpace wage growth.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to information from the Minister of the Environment and Water Management, Gábor Fodor, the meetings of experts will be completed on Tuesday, and after the official opening on Wednesday, the international conference on the post-2012 climate regime will continue with ministerial meetings.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which addresses the efforts following the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol valid until 2012.
At the moment, there is a heated debate about them between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also announced that it does not wish to discuss exact numbers now, although it is leaning toward an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 relative to 1990 levels.
Another big question of the conference is whether developed countries will, in addition to reducing emissions, also provide both material and technological aid to countries that depend on it.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, established by the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member management board, most likely within the framework of the World Environmental Protection Program (GEF) at the United Nations - we can read in the Piac és Profit magazine.
Hungarian six percent
The Minister of the Environment and Water Management, Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU&#39;s efforts to maintain a leading role in efforts to protect the global climate and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said the EU is committed to cutting greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent from 1990 levels by 2020, regardless of the success of a &quot;post-2012 deal&quot; and is ready to commit to up to a 30 percent reduction if others developed regions of the world, respectively developed countries willing to accept responsibility and obligations corresponding to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 set a reduction target of 5.2 percent, with the then 15 EU member states committing to 8 percent.
Hungary&#39;s commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-87, which our country will fulfill. – is mentioned in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
A lot is at stake in Bali, or an international agreement on a long-term climate change policy needs to be adopted within two years, otherwise its entry into force would definitely be postponed until 2012. In that case, the reduction commitments established by the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new a system of reducing emissions, the necessity of which was also pointed out in its latest report by the UN international scientific body dealing with climate change - IPCC, which is the winner of the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and an inevitable increase in the Earth&#39;s average temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius, which the scientists say would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
British military units are posting footage of their actions in Iraq and Afghanistan on a video-sharing site to promote themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) took a liking to YouTube: special forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban here since March 2006, the BBC reported.
The footage, captured by a miniature helmet-mounted camera, is reviewed by the Air Force Command, which controls combat operations in the Kandahar region, and then forwarded to London, where it is uploaded to the Internet.
A political message is inevitable
In this way, 139 recordings of British Air Force soldiers have already reached the Internet, and more than 75,000 people have watched their &quot;channel&quot;.
The UK Ministry of Defense registered as &quot;defenceheadquarters&quot; in spring 2007 and publishes footage from both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the UK Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Force in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force released the videos as originally intended for recruiting purposes, and the Defense Department says they are also good for informing the general public about the true purpose of the military&#39;s presence abroad.
&quot;Promotion published in this form costs next to nothing compared to traditional television recruitment ads,&quot; defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, &quot;but it also necessarily carries a certain political message, or in a special way confirms the legitimacy of military actions decided by the government.&quot;
The Americans made a play
The army is worried that in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos are also being uploaded to the server, depicting, for example, the death of soldiers: in somewhat hypocritical, &quot;official&quot; promotional films, the officers only talk about losses, but the bloody image of the battle is not shown.
After all, many videos from the battles in Iraq and Afghanistan, which were created during a sharp deployment, have already reached the Internet, but the British army found them only now.
The Americans do recruitment a little differently - with a free-to-download shooter game called America&#39;s Army, in which the player can step directly into the soldiers&#39; shoes through a more or less faithful simulation.
