The Czech Republic has a chance to get 365 billion
Yesterday, the ministers of the Czech government and representatives of the European Commission signed a total of nine operational programs, from which the Czech Republic can receive 14 billion euros (approximately 365 billion crowns) in the coming years.
This is roughly half of the total amount that the Czech Republic can receive from Brussels between 2007 and 2013.
Approximately 125 billion crowns will go from seven operational programs to the regions.
Czech companies will be able to get around 100 billion crowns from the Entrepreneurship and Innovation program.
The most money, up to 150 billion, will go to transport.
The Transport program is the largest operational program and represents up to 22 percent of the funds that the Czech Republic can receive from the funds.
This money will increase the budget of the State Transport Infrastructure Fund, which will manage the sum of 90.8 billion crowns next year.
The Entrepreneurship and Innovation program is intended to serve entrepreneurs and companies to obtain funds for innovative business.
Companies should obtain funding for the introduction of new technologies, for industrial research, but also for the introduction of more effective organizational methods.
So far, the Czech Republic has been among the least successful countries in drawing money from EU funds.
