So they approved our budget
It is so.
The state budget was adopted.
What makes this budget special?
It is the first budget drawn up by this government and adopted by a coalition majority without the support of the opposition.
The one for this year passed last year with the support of the ČSSD, because it was prepared by Minister Sobotka and the ČSSD could not afford not to accept it.
Unlike the lively debate before the vote of no confidence in the government, nothing dramatic happened this time.
The Chamber of Deputies quietly approved this traditionally overlooked, although most influential, law.
It is a certain paradox.
All governance begins and ends with individual chapters and budget items, whether one likes it or not.
The budget is an essential part of politics, but it is hidden behind the power struggle between the government and the opposition.
It is more media-friendly and therefore receives much more attention in the media.
The guesswork of politicians is much more interesting to the public than stark numbers.
State budgets in previous social democratic governments suffered from three ailments, which the one in 2008 is unable to solve at once:
The first of them is the high share of legally required, so-called mandatory expenses, which are not only pensions, but also social benefits, which were approved by the silent &quot;coalition&quot; of the ČSSD and KSČM last year before the elections.
The second of them is deficit management as a consequence of the illness of the first.
The third limit is public finance deficits, i.e. the budget deficit of cities and municipalities.
However, the biggest risk is not the state budget deficit.
It is public and relatively under control.
However, the budget deficit of cities and municipalities is a ticking time bomb.
Many mayors, in order to obtain additional resources for investments, in addition to money from taxes, fees and loans from banks, often recklessly issued bonds, with which they disproportionately indebted their town halls.
In past years, they managed to pay off these debts by mass selling shares in energy and other distribution networks, which they received from the state through privatization.
Now they no longer have this resource.
If we stick only to official and verifiable facts, we will find that:
Our economy, like the rest of the world, has been going through a growth phase for several years, which the ČSSD constantly boasts about.
This was a unique opportunity for its governments to put their public finances in order.
Instead, however, the state was increasingly indebted.
Other countries, with a few exceptions such as Hungary, Albania, Pakistan or Egypt, managed their economy much more sensibly than our republic.
It is a huge shame that falls mainly on the past governments.
We are among the countries that are, on a global scale, the least threatened by poverty.
That is why there is no need for massive social programs, which, unfortunately, have swelled to gigantic proportions in recent years.
Even if part of the senseless populist spending, approved this year before the elections, has been canceled, if the retirement limit and pension reform are not moved in the near future, then virtually any politics in this country will end, and whoever is in power will be merely incumbency.
With little exaggeration, it can be said that ruling politicians will become officials, mechanically distributing most of the taxed money for pensions and social benefits.
Therefore, this year&#39;s budget cannot be revolutionary, but can only suspend the displacement of normal spending by mandatory spending.
The planned deficit of 70 billion for the year 2008 would be completely useless if the previous governments had not managed as much as they could in the last ten years.
If we don&#39;t really want the governing politicians to become mere officials, then we have to be patient and let this not-so-strong coalition government, which realizes that the state can only spend as much as it gets in taxes and fees, calm for the preparation of further reform laws.
Only these will enable the gradual achievement of a balanced state budget.
