Banks want to solve the crisis
The American Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
Thus, more than one hundred billion dollars will reach the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks bid on the interest rate at which they are willing to lend money.
For example, the US Fed will send forty billion dollars to the auction, and then make another twenty-four billion available to the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the attacks of September 11 that the central banks of individual countries have agreed on such a coordinated procedure to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
&quot;This move is intended to address the economy&#39;s biggest problem, i.e. the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend,&quot; Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group consultancy wrote in his report to clients.
&quot;Coordinated action by central banks reduced the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,&quot; Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost sixty billion dollars due to defaulted loans, mainly in the United States.
Analysts expect further losses of billions.
&quot;Central banks must be really scared of what may come next when they decide to take this course,&quot; said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
&quot;It looks like the situation is really bad,&quot; he added.
Central banks are concerned that if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will also lend to their customers more expensively.
This would reduce consumption and send the US economy into recession with possible effects on economic growth around the world.
The central banks decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate, which is used for lending money in the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still wary of lending money to each other, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
&quot;It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates,&quot; Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the move by central banks will help to avert the crisis because it does not address the underlying problem, which is the collapse of the US housing market.
