Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
It is truly an island of freedom for visitors.
Whatever you expect from your vacation, it can come true if you choose it right.
Golden and white beaches, high waves, or the sea, as calm as a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and intoxicating cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea you will find it in a complete and even richer list.
But you can find much more on just one island, and that island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
Under the Spanish, Cuba used to be a bastion of their conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye had ever seen.
Havana became a warehouse and transshipment point for the treasures that the Spanish looted in America and transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the very end of the 1920s.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was a crime in the USA (especially during prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba by drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise buildings rose in Havana, cars that were among the cult symbols of the 1950s drove along the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, not far from Havana, and had his yacht in Cojímar.
Show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of Havana&#39;s Bodeguita.
At the bar of the expensive Hotel Nacional, they will mix you a cocktail of your choice.
And those iconic cars from the 1950s still drive around Havana, because the once-imported Zhiguli and Fiats have long since rotted in the salty and humid air.
Although Havana, especially its oldest part, is very dilapidated, there are still as many beautiful colonial monuments in the vicinity as there.
Other places are also transformed into beauty, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings in much-needed money, its development has the green light.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but especially in Varadero, on the coast of the Holguín province, and on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers one more pleasure that is unique in the world and will be especially appreciated by train riders.
Cane from vast plantations was brought to the sugar mills by steam and motor trains on narrow tracks.
Their vehicle fleet has not been renewed for many decades, so you can see working machines, the likes of which can only be found elsewhere in museums.
Where to go?
Most visitors to Cuba do not miss the most famous places.
And so there is no need to write much about Varadero or Havana.
Just to remind you that there is a museum in the already mentioned Hemingway estate, and anyone who likes this writer should not miss a visit.
Viňales Valley One of the most picturesque corners of Cuba is the Viňales Valley in the west of the island.
Lush vegetation grows from the limestone bedrock.
Mogots, limestone boulders and rocks rise steeply from the valley floor, and fertile soil has taken hold in their cavities, thanks to which even the weathered cliffs are covered with dense vegetation.
The valley is where perhaps the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You can meet its final form if you visit one of the cigar factories in Havana.
Maybe someone will find it interesting that the Chilean part of Major Zeman was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded not long after the Spanish colonized the island.
The slave and sugar trade brought him fame and fortune.
Wealth was transformed into the beauty and showiness of a small town.
Colonial Spanish architecture, significantly influenced by later French settlers, has hardly changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is a place so remote that even in the 1950s there was no road connecting it to the rest of the country.
That isolation helped him stay away.
Nothing was being built there, and therefore nothing was being torn down either, everyone was happy to have a roof over their heads.
If you have more time in Trinidad than one afternoon, then it is worth looking at the interesting places in the vicinity, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the valley of the Sugar Bowls.
In the evening, you should go to the Casa de la Música, which comes to life after dark and the music dies down in the morning.
Baracoa
The town in the very east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
The journey itself certainly influences such an opinion.
Both roads that lead there from Guantánamo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and pass through nature that has hardly been affected by human activity.
Thanks to its unspoilt nature, the eastern island of Cuba has been included in the World Heritage List by UNESCO.
They make the best chocolate there, they have a Columbus cross in the church (actually it was created about a hundred years after Columbus&#39; voyage) and from the hill where the former castle and today&#39;s hotel El Castillo stand, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, about the Sierra Maestra mountains, about the Bay of Pigs and Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, about the shrine of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of former slaves, all of this would be could take many pages to describe.
But, as they say, better seen once.
