Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crew members from the International Space Station (ISS) spent more than seven hours working in space to make a remarkable repair of a torn solar panel necessary for the station&#39;s continued scientific activities.
It was a risky spacewalk that set records for duration, distance from habitable modules, the speed with which it was planned and the amount of &quot;tinkering&quot; that astronauts spent on repairs.
The trouble emerged on Tuesday as astronauts from Discovery unloaded the Harmony module, a large cylindrical structure designed to house a European and Japanese science laboratory (see box).
