Loaded memory
After more than sixty years of secrecy, the Nazi archives from Bad Arolsen, which recount the fates of 17.5 million victims of Hitler&#39;s regime, are being opened to the public.
The 47 million archive documents stored over a length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were until now only accessible for &quot;humanitarian&quot; purposes, that is, individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his authorized persons.
Eleven states in charge of managing the archives - which include Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening became effective yesterday.
Sensitive information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to examine &quot;in particular the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health of the forced laborers&quot;, explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Comité international de la Croix-rouge, CICR).
Until recently, several states, Germany among them, were opposed to making these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some of the information.
What are the assumed homosexuality or mental disabilities of some victims of deportation.
Concentration camp registers or arrest warrants compiled by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor civilians, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen represents only a limited benefit.
&quot;Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents&quot;, said prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin.
