Congress approved the transposition of MiFID effective from 1 November
In parallel with parliamentary deliberations, which ended today with Congress voting on amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government submitted to a public hearing the regulation that develops the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of individual parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of MPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard in order to guarantee the protection of investors and the detailed regulation of the activities of entities needed for the efficient functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernization of financial markets and at the same time strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Commission for the Securities Market (CNMV) and supports cooperation between the individual supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will allow the provision of financial advisory services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of Financial Services Firms (ESIS), Financial Advisory Firms (AFI), which join securities companies, securities brokerage offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for executing operations in financial instruments is expanding, with regulated secondary markets being joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems that will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law further obliges companies providing investment services to disseminate information on the market about key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and methods of dealing with risk, and requires keeping a report of all operations performed to simplify supervision by the CNMV.
During the deliberations in the Congressional Commerce Committee, several modifications were included, among which the securitized receivables are considered a &quot;complex&quot; financial instrument due to the high danger for the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the US with subprime mortgage debts (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delineate the positions that bachelors in economics and business management can hold, 30 years after a royal decree was approved in 1977 delineating professional positions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require a permit from the CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
