The recommendation from the president of the Supreme Audit Office, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was linked to the June attacks at Glasgow Airport.
Mr Black is also concerned that the Scottish NHS does not have an accurate idea of the number of foreign staff it employs.
But his report highlighted that other key checks went well across a sample of five health authorities.
Immediately after the June attacks on Glasgow Airport, the President of the Supreme Audit Office was interested in personnel recruited from countries outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was detained at the airport after someone drove a Jeep into the doors of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court via videobridge accused of being linked to attempted bombings in the UK.
NHS Chambers are expected to check foreign staff for qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although Scottish health commissions use Disclosure Scotland for criminal record checks, the agency has no power to obtain such information outside of Britain.
The report by the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that commissions should be guided by the guidelines of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with checks in several countries.
&quot;Although we found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not being carried out regularly,&quot; the report said.
Mr Black said NHS Scotland largely agreed with its own pre-employment vetting policy, but added: &quot;Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure accurate information is available on the number of foreign staff.&quot;
Chairman of BMA Scotland dr. Peter Terry said it was &quot;highly unlikely&quot; that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS staff who might commit an act of terrorism in the future.
&quot;The report suggests that current pre-employment checks in the Scottish NHS are working well and it is unclear what further value the comments will bring,&quot; he said.
Scottish Health authorities have reported that they currently have 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Audit Office pointed out that these numbers will probably be higher also because the commissions had a problem identifying personnel with residence permits.
The survey also found that established inspection procedures at NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are being carried out to a large extent.
These included checks on passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently revising the pre-employment checks policy and guidelines for overseas NHS workers.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: &quot;I wanted to get this job done in the immediate aftermath of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport.&quot;
She also added that the Scottish Government, in consultation with health commissions, will consider the report&#39;s recommendations and ensure best practice appears in updated guidelines on pre-employment checks for all staff - including overseas - which it plans to issue next month.
Joy Division dominate the film awards
Control, the biopic about the late Joy Division singer Ian Curtis, picked up five awards at the British Independent Film Awards, including Best Film.
