Saudi Arabia arrests 208 people over terror plot
Saudi Arabia announced yesterday that it had arrested 208 militants for being members of cells preparing an imminent attack on oil facilities as well as clerics and security forces.
The state television of the largest oil exporter said that one of the cells wanted to smuggle missiles into the country.
Al-Qaeda sympathizers have been campaigning against the monarchy, an ally of the United States, since the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
A television report reported that a cell of eight militants led by a foreigner was planning an attack on an oil facility in Ash-Sharqiyah province.
Saudi Arabia is building a 35,000-strong rapid-reaction force to defend facilities since a failed 2006 al-Qaeda attack on the world&#39;s largest oil refinery in Abqaiq.
The report cited an internal ministry statement: 18 of those arrested belonged to a cell led by a &quot;missile launch expert&quot; who slipped into the country.
It further said that the militants planned to smuggle eight missiles into the kingdom.
The 22 detainees were supposed to be preparing the murders of clergy and security personnel.
The government has urged clerics to do more to prevent Saudis from going to Iraq to join al-Qaeda militants fighting allied troops and the US-backed Shiite government, which conservative Sunni Saudis consider heretical.
Al-Qaeda militants believe that authorities have co-opted many clerics in Saudi Arabia to support the royal family that controls the government.
The militants - encouraged by al-Qaeda leader Saud Osama bin Laden&#39;s calls to target the pro-Western Saudi government - have targeted foreign housing complexes, government buildings and energy facilities.
&quot;This war has been a huge effort by the security forces in the past... five months,&quot; an internal ministry spokesman told state television.
Also arrested was a 16-member &quot;media cell&quot; in Medina that aimed to promote &quot;takfiri thinking&quot; - the ideology of Sunni Muslim radicals that promotes violence against Muslims labeled as infidels and apostates.
Among those arrested were also 32 people accused of providing financial support to militants.
The climate on Venus may be a glimpse into Earth&#39;s future
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may once have been a pleasant place for life.
Data from the orbiting European station show that the planet is even more like Earth&#39;s wayward twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth&#39;s closest planetary neighbor.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit in similar orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and may have been habitable.
But the alarming greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and a slower rotation rate sent Venus down a completely different path of evolution.
Today, the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is ravaged by hurricane-force storms and winds.
Findings from the European Space Agency&#39;s Venus Express probe, which studied the planet for a year, offer a sobering look at how Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from Oxford University&#39;s Department of Physics and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: &quot;It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different to Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
&quot;Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus started out like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment, billions of years ago.&quot;
