Still wide open
Mitt Romney said it&#39;s not dignified for presidential candidates to answer questions from a snowman.
Even so, the Republican presidential candidates eventually agreed to a YouTube debate in which ordinary voters videotaped their questions and gave them to the candidates for broadcast.
None of the questions aired on Wednesday, Nov. 28 were as comical as the snowman who asked Democrats about global warming in the other party&#39;s YouTube debate.
But both the questions and the answers this time reflected a lot about the state of the Republican Party heading into next year&#39;s election.
It is not clear exactly how the producers of CNN, one of the sponsors of the debate, selected the clips that were then shown to the aspiring candidates.
But the first half hour of the debate, the longest time devoted to a single topic, focused on immigration.
This issue is one of the strongest Republican issues.
CNN asked a panel of undecided voters to turn the dial when they heard something heartening: the anchor saw approval spikes when the candidates talked about getting tough on the border.
The toughest and longest exchange came between Rudy Giuliani, the national front-runner, and Mr. Romney, who edged ahead in key early votes in Iowa and New Hampshire.
Mr. Giuliani is trying to shake off a reputation as a man who was soft on illegal immigrants as mayor of New York.
He attacked Mr. Romney, accusing the former Massachusetts governor of hiring illegal immigrants to work on his home.
The two sparred especially fiercely when pollsters asked whether either candidate would support &quot;amnesty&quot; (giving illegal immigrants normal status and the possibility of citizenship).
Minority candidates such as Duncan Hunter, Congressman from California, and Tom Tancredo, Congressman from Colorado, have been able to throw their bit in the mill on this issue.
Neither of the two have a shot at the nomination, but both remain in the game perhaps because they started sounding the alarm about immigration earlier and stronger than others.
At least on immigration, the candidates have roughly the same opinion: more strictness at the border, no tolerance for illegal migrants.
This issue, along with concerns about poisonous toys from China and other worries about the outside world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the divide between libertarians and Christian conservatives.
But the debate became very unpleasant when it came to other topics.
Mr. Giuliani was asked why he supported gun ownership in the past.
John McCain and Mr Romney debated whether the simulated heating technique should be considered torture.
One interviewer asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
Mr. Giuliani stumbles through this to the point that even though the Bible is his favorite book, he probably doesn&#39;t literally believe the story of Jonah and the whale.
Another questioner asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - now against all odds in first place in a recent Iowa poll thanks to his longtime Christian conservatism - said the death penalty is unpleasant but necessary.
Pressed to decide whether Jesus would agree, he said that Jesus was too smart to run, earning a laugh.
The fight remains remarkably open.
Mr. Huckabee&#39;s surge in Iowa coincides with recent fundraising successes and Ron Paul&#39;s loud cheers at Wednesday&#39;s debate.
These two have bounced back from the bottom as the two wings of the party still can&#39;t agree on better-known, more traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one candidate united the party very early and convincingly with a winning message of American greatness on his lips, winking at both wings of the party.
This time the party is divided and the result is far from clear.
Labour&#39;s pains
Gordon Brown has once again found a trap to fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although this is the norm in British political scandals, this one is not particularly spicy.
No marriage orders appear to have been sold, no Paris hotel bills mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers sucked.
But a barricaded Gordon Brown would have gotten away without it being discovered that a wealthy businessman had concealed £650,000 ($1.3 million) in contributions to the ruling Labor Party under other people&#39;s names for four years, without the party reporting it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling an election and offended the British intelligentsia by claiming that the decision was not influenced by polls, there were hopes that he would secure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly witty Lib Dem deputy leader put it, the once-feared Mr Brown has turned from Stalin to Mr Bean.
The clumsy rescue of troubled bank Northern Rock exposed management weaknesses and poor judgment under fire.
Ill-conceived proposals to change the tax code have united companies against the government.
The loss of personal data of 25 million people exposed unimaginable administrative blunders.
A trio of retired generals started a mutiny in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending, arguing that being commander-in-chief was a part-time job.
Now here are the multifaceted gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour&#39;s general secretary (and their former internal discipline watchdog), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is headed inexorably toward his end.
Even so, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governing difficult.
The people don&#39;t trust politicians and don&#39;t like them, but they usually put aside their distrust when a new group takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not even be in office long, this relegation is gone: the civil service becomes leaky, ministers start giving briefings, the press looks for bad news, and the government becomes unfocused and defensive.
In one sense, Mr. Brown&#39;s position is particularly difficult because, compared to other political leaders, he cannot assume the position of a new broom.
As much as he would like to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the Inland Revenue records are linked to decisions Mr Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he wasn&#39;t directly involved in Blairite woes, such as the long-running investigation into party funding caused by &quot;ranks for money&quot;, voters can safely assume he was.
Still, Mr. Brown&#39;s predicament is not as bad as it seems.
The fumbles aren&#39;t as horrible as conservatives make them out to be.
As for Mr. Bean, no one died or was outright fooled.
And the cure, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Mr Brown&#39;s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: reliable, firm and slightly brutal government.
The latest uproar over political donations is a good example.
Garboid Mr Abrahams, who likens his donations to charity, says he wanted no publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not his.
Laws against the anonymity of big political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who might be buying access to those who govern the country.
Mr Watt, who said he was aware of Mr Abrahams&#39;s conduct but did not know it was illegal, is sure to be thoroughly questioned; so did Jon Mendlesohn, Labour&#39;s chief fundraiser, who became aware of the dodgy donations in October.
But so far Mr. Brown is not implicated; there is nothing to suggest that he was aware of these shenanigans, although the bulk of the payments did not take place until after he took office in June.
The Prime Minister has done half the work so far.
He was quick to condemn this breach of law by his own party, but he diluted his resolve by reaching for a proven tool, a commission to investigate the matter - led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had one for six months, and moving forward with real reform of political party funding.
That would require embattled Labor to co-operate with the Tories and perhaps give up their special financial relationship with the unions - a bitter pill for a stalwart like Mr Brown.
But he should face some simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way to win is through unassailable integrity and high competence.
Card sharks
Is the subprime mortgage crisis affecting the US credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally start to flutter around excitedly.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is languishing, predators have set their sights on the U.S. credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if subprime mortgages spread to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of strain are evident.
The number of defaults (more than 30 days late in payment) and written-off accounts (accounts deemed uncollectible by the provider) are on the rise.
Last month, HSBC announced that it had lost $1.4 billion in the US consumer credit market - also due to bad credit card loans.
However, it is still too early to panic.
There are still few written-off accounts and defaults.
The 3.89% default rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below average, according to Moody&#39;s.
Deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
A change in US personal bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to a sharp drop in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large portion of credit card losses; therefore, the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would rise regardless of whether general conditions for borrowers worsened.
The industry also shows a good repayment rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts each month.
And confidence in secured credit card securities is solid, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup research firm predicts that their emissions volumes for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct contagion routes between the subprime crisis and the credit card market: when home equity loans dry up, consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt.
However, credit card issuers look at cash flow rather than collateral values, so falling home prices don&#39;t necessarily mean a change in borrower credibility.
They may even be beneficial to lenders.
Consumers&#39; motivation to repay their mortgages decreases when their property value falls below the loan value; as a result, card debt moves up the list of priorities to pay off.
Card issuers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of rapid changes in the prices of guaranteed items.
&quot;It&#39;s not going to happen one fine morning that we just renegotiate all the loans,&quot; says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
While the risk of a subprime-style explosion is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower home prices and debt deleveraging push America into recession, the credit card industry faces a bleaker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were to be tried for their roles in a fraud involving former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Fastow changed their pleas and pleaded guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew initially pleaded not guilty to seven counts of fraud in which they and Fastow participated in a financial fraud in 2000 -- enriching themselves at the expense of their employers.
They were due to appear in court in January.
However, during a retrial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr. each pleaded guilty to one count of fraud.
The case of the three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, made headlines throughout the two years of the extradition proceedings.
In the United States, their case is one of the unclosed parts of the investigation started after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
Charges brought against them in 2002 alerted Mr. Fastow that he was the target of a government investigation into the collapse of Enron.
The indictment against the bankers -- who earned the nickname &quot;The NatWest Troika&quot; -- alleges they came to Houston in 2000 to orchestrate the fraud with Fastow and his former top aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in an Enron affiliate controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of the many Enron frauds that sent Enron spiraling toward bankruptcy.
In early 2002, the bank valued its stake in this branch at zero, but our three Brits knew it was actually worth a lot.
A company under Kopper&#39;s control bought the bank&#39;s stake in that branch for $1 million.
The incriminated bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in the Greenwich branch of NatWest.
But the 20 million actually went to those British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, according to the indictment, and Fastow, Kopper and others pocketed roughly $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a sentence of three years and one month at a facility in Texarkana.
All three Britons were free on $1 million bail, ordering them to remain in the United States pending an upcoming trial.
Enron, once the nation&#39;s seventh-largest company, collapsed into bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting gimmicks made it no longer possible to hide billions of dollars in debt or show failed speculations as profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value and more than $2 billion in pension benefits.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company&#39;s downfall.
Skilling is serving more than twenty-four years in prison.
Lay&#39;s convictions on conspiracy, fraud and other charges were expunged after he died of heart disease last year.
Moscow&#39;s non-helplessness
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and with enough fuel for a non-stop flight from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
However, for some of the Russian rich, it is a pittance to return.
&quot;It can carry up to 18 passengers,&quot; says Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
&quot;But none of them are interested in so many places because it&#39;s for a close family or a company president.&quot;
Mr. Firer was sitting in the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire Show, a four-day orgy of lavish consumption at a mammoth exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, over 200 other luxury purveyors set up their booths, hoping to lure newly wealthy Russians with everything from mahogany-inlaid yachts to diamond-encrusted car dashes that 50 Cent wouldn&#39;t be ashamed of.
Mr. Firer cautiously looked back at the bright orange Porsche in the next booth.
&quot;It&#39;s a nice car, but it&#39;s fives and tenners against us,&quot; he said.
&quot;After the United States, Russia is the second largest private jet market.&quot;
Money is pouring into the Russian capital on the waves of oil, just like when Dallas had its days.
&quot;We went through the same stage in the 1980s, when some Americans became enormously wealthy and gravitated to Europe, where they were seen as materialists,&quot; said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year fellow at Harvard&#39;s Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies.
Like the Saudi spenders of the 1970s and the Japanese in the 1990s, the Russians are becoming the world&#39;s most prominent spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share in this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, a luxury industry conference drew Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, chairman of the LVMH group, to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets such as Russia.
