&quot;All the women are impeccably groomed and the men are each worth a fortune.&quot;
As they walked through the halls in evening dresses on Sunday evening, 21-year-old Evgenia Yumatovová and five-year-old Svetlana Turovtsova described themselves and their clients as millionaires.
&quot;I&#39;ve been looking at the cars and I can&#39;t decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche,&quot; said Miss Yumatov, who was decked out in designer clothes like a red carpet veteran, next to whom Joan Rivers looks like a homebody.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the newly rich, brand-driven Russian buyers willing to sit in traffic for several hours to stroll through a warehouse that blaringly mixes Cadillac Escalades, platinum fish, Mövenpick ice cream, custom pool tables, apartments in Dubai, Gund stuffed animals and drafts.
Members of the general public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
&quot;Russians are interested in which brand is the most expensive and the best,&quot; declared Mr. Gijrath, who patriotically occupied the stall of Dutch porcelain maker Royal Delft in front of a larger-than-life reproduction of a Rembrandt painting from hand-painted blue tiles.
