Even so, several thousand people, whether millionaires, ambassadors of millionaires or simple tourists, flooded the fair halls every day.
And some of them shopped.
On the first day of the show, last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the local general manager of King Koil beds, said he sold two mattress sets made of silk, cashmere and cotton, woven with gold threads, for $70,000 each.
Also on the first day, Mikhail Lyubimov, sales manager for A1 Moto, which equips high-end cars with high-end alarms, said his company sold a bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrej Karapetian, president of LA Connection, a custom luxury car modification company, said he sold three chain-link-style grilles for Rolls-Royce Phantoms for $55,000 each.
He showed the reporter a wheel of a car designed for a Russian casino owner that had Swarovski crystal-encrusted spokes that looked like a roulette wheel.
Price: $22,000 for four of these.
&quot;The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich skin bikes or a cubic zirconia portrait of his wife doesn&#39;t have to ride those bikes yet,&quot; Mr. Karapetian said.
“He stores them in his thirty to forty car garage.
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase &quot;Russian millionaire&quot; doesn&#39;t mean anything too exclusive these days, given the big rise in property prices here.
&quot;If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you are probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash,&quot; he said.
“There are more than you think.
Those who aren&#39;t millionaires could at least feign wealth at a booth run by Russian asset management firm Alliance Continental.
The company erected four red British-style phone booths stuffed with columns of fake million-dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company&#39;s marketing manager, said his team printed 500,000 fake banknotes for the Millionaire Fair.
Passers-by stopped to throw around piles of cash, or to have friends take cell phone pictures of them relaxing in the midst of spare wealth, or simply to stuff their pockets with a few million.
&quot;You know, everyone can feel like a millionaire in Moscow,&quot; Mr. Karryev said.
New Jersey death possibly caused by botched operation
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Roland Livingston looked out the large windows of the A Little Healthier restaurant here and watched an ambulance pull up to a white New England house two houses down West Scott Avenue.
