Hopes that the Fed will cut interest rates lead to a strengthening of global stock markets
Share prices on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday after market hopes that the Federal Reserve will try to ease lending conditions by further cutting interest rates were boosted by reassuring remarks from the vice chairman of the US Federal Reserve.
Stocks jumped in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, the Fed&#39;s second-in-command to Ben Bernanke, said policymakers needed to be &quot;flexible and pragmatic&quot; in responding to continued pressure on financial markets.
In an apparent effort to calm jittery markets amid signs of a resurgent credit strain, Mr. Kohn said the recent jitters &quot;partially reversed some of the improvements in market performance toward the end of September and into October.&quot;
