England must decide: Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
We have two dilemmas here, one almost as difficult as the other.
Who will bat at number six for England this weekend in Kandy, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, in a larger context no less relevant than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who gets to make that decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the chairman of the selection committee, who is at best on borrowed time, has Peter Moores, the head coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, to help with the decision-making and because the desk of Hugh Morris, the chief manager of the English team, starts filling in applications for the post of national selector, although not necessarily full-time.
The one who doesn&#39;t bat in the sixth place will be unhappy, but life is often not fair, and sports certainly aren&#39;t.
It is not easy to find what takes one to the top of his profession, while another never gets past the lower level, sometimes due to lack of luck rather than ability.
Not only in cricket, the selection is difficult and requires judgment, which in the end must always be subjective.
Is the time right for Bopara to move up?
Is it fair to Shah if so?
We could ask the same thing in another area, say here: John Edwards or &quot;Tubby&quot; Banerjee, both bright young executives with good education and industry insight, should be promoted to the commission - there&#39;s only room for one .
Who is to say which level is right for a cricketer when he is given no chance to sink or float to the next one?
Naturally, numbers have a big impact on decision-making, but so do opportunities.
In a team, a cricketer needs to catch the captain&#39;s eye at the right moment if he is to take a wicket, and a batsman needs regular chances at opening positions if he is ever to make an impression as a one-day cricketer.
Catching the selector&#39;s eye is more complicated.
Last season, for example, there were many better than James Anderson, whose place in the first Test looks certain even if Stephen Harmison declares himself fit and bowls like a gunner.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs apiece.
Chris Tremlett took just 29 at an equally meager average, but both have had their moments at the highest level and will be hoping for more.
Whether he will play at Asgiriya Shah Stadium or Bopara can only be a matter of opinion.
The choice may start or end the careers of both, or it may not have much of an impact.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every Test and performed well in first-class, taking five wickets and conceding 40 runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, struggling for his place at the same time, who eventually emerged as a consistent Test cricketer, who, moreover, despite scoring two hundreds against Australia, is perhaps still underrated.
Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after one more discussion following today&#39;s clean sheet at the Asirgiya Stadium, are more likely to follow their conservative instincts and prefer Shah&#39;s greater experience to Bopar&#39;s youthful exuberance.
There are arguments for both.
His scintillating and valuable debut Test innings of 88 in Mumbai and 32 first-class hundreds against Bopar&#39;s six speak for Shah, who, at 22, is seven years his junior and has excellent stats against spin pitches.
However, Shah made just ten runs in two innings in May against the Caribbean in a Test at Lord&#39;s, his Middlesex home ground, and that, coupled with the selectors&#39; immediate rejection when Vaughan wanted to re-insert him for the next match, his batting seems to have taken a hit from the vigor that was so evident in Bombay.
In contrast, the Essex all-rounder has joie de vivre in his bones.
Nothing fazes him on the cricket field and his behavior off the field is epitomized by the recent overturn of a four-wheel drive car at an exhibition day for the England team&#39;s car sponsor, Volkswagen.
He escaped with minor injuries and probably shock, but the first thing he did was pull out his Vodafone (sponsored, of course) and call Alastair Cook, his teammate, who was watching from a distance, to excitedly ask, &quot;Did you see that?&quot;
Bopara is definitely better in the field, delivering his medium-quick slip pitches on the pitches here, which he seems to suit, effectively and batting with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right person is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Perhaps this is the true art of selection.
Personally, I&#39;m leaning towards Bopara getting his chance now, which is not to say that Shah won&#39;t excel if, as the Ceylon tea leaves suggest, he&#39;s the one playing here next weekend.
