Venus is Earth&#39;s infernal twin
Despite its life-unfriendly atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought. The European space probe Venus Express on Venus recorded phenomena that also occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that there is lightning on Venus.
Now the European probe Venus Express has brought proof - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning flies from cloud to cloud at a height of about 56 kilometers, Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles wrote in the scientific magazine Nature.
According to the well-known theory of the origin of primordial matter, life could have arisen on Earth thanks to lightning. Storms are said to have triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
This was not the case on Venus: &quot;If life ever existed there, it must have been a very long time ago,&quot; explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there would hardly be anything alive on the surface of Venus. The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and sometimes the temperature here is around 500 °C.
&quot;Venus may be Earth&#39;s twin from hell, but it&#39;s a twin,&quot; Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, began to develop completely differently is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
Since no probe has been sent exclusively to study Venus since the early 1990s, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the study of the planet.
According to scientists, the latest research results, which were presented in several articles in the journal Nature, did not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
&quot;They also showed that our neighboring planet is more Earth-like than previously thought,&quot; Esa said.
In addition to the already known wind vortices at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole, which rotates significantly faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth&#39;s northern hemisphere, writes the research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni from Italy&#39;s Instituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of our solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and with a diameter of 12,100 km is almost the same size.
This planet known as Morning Star or Večernica orbits the Sun in almost 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis. One day on Venus lasts 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus does not resemble Earth with a surface temperature of 460 °C and a pressure of 92 bars (short for bar?), scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both. On Earth, however, it remained in the oceans, while it evaporated into space from Venus.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
