Richard Gere just isn&#39;t cynical enough
With the release of The Hunting Party and Mörderischer Frieden, there were two films about the war in the Balkans.
But neither of them is convincing.
The design of the films either places too much emphasis on action and shooting, or they are too emotional.
Not even an actor like Richard Gere can prevent that in The Hunting Party.
Good news first: War criminals Karadzić and Mladić are still hiding in the mountains of the Balkans, but it is there, in the dark background of the Bosnian War, that actor Richard Gere finds himself.
Lately we&#39;ve lost sight of this most handsome man of the 80s, not only because he&#39;s been in a lot of cute, frivolous roles in easy-going women&#39;s movies, but coupled with his perpetually Buddhism-themed press conferences, it makes one want to see another movie with this actor.
And yet Richard Gere is suddenly the strongest argument for watching The Hunting Party (Why do movie titles have to be so long and convoluted these days?).
Gere gives a magical performance. His war reporter Simon Hunt is essentially what Gere might have become if fate and the film industry hadn&#39;t been so kind: a man whose prime years are long behind him, but who, as a wreck-like monument, still retains a certain remarkable charm .
But despite this trump card, The Hunting Party, along with the German film Mörderischer Frieden, which also hits theaters this week, is just the continuation of an endless string of unsuccessful films about the war in the Balkans.
We can make a short trial with the movie Mörderischer Frieden: This movie is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt) who save a Serbian girl from a Kosovar sniper, after which one of them falls in love with her.
While it&#39;s commendable that the Serbs aren&#39;t presented as the cause of all evil here, this television-shallow film turns into gunplay and action too soon.
Something very similar to the series Kobra 11 will remain from the film, albeit without the highway, but with war instead.
In the film The Hunting Party, one can clearly examine why a really good film about the Balkan War has not yet been made.
The story of three American war reporters who go after &quot;the fox&quot;, a Serbian war criminal in charge, could possibly become a new &quot;Apocalypse&quot; in a different time and under the guidance of a different director and screenwriter (here both are Richard Shepard).
After all, both stories are surprisingly similar: small groups go into the forest to do something that the army is not capable of, but their journey becomes a path to madness.
One of the reasons for the failure of The Hunting Party is that Simon Hunt is not the debauched and sentimental cynic introduced at the beginning.
On the contrary, the draft also prescribes him a romantic affair with a Bosnian Muslim woman who was later murdered.
We can finally write off The Hunting Party after the reporters succeed in the last five sped-up minutes of the film what NATO, the CIA and all the world&#39;s criminal hunters have failed to do in the last five years: catch the criminal and leave him to the righteous vengeance of the Bosnian Muslims.
This is so against the logic of filmmaking that it would be worth going to the International Court of Justice in The Hague.
At the same time, this film has a deeply human message.
It condemns that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and suspects the Americans and the French (they are exceptionally united here) of not pursuing the prosecution intensively enough based on secret political agreements.
But good and evil are sometimes so similar, the famous Brecht poem comes to mind.
In it, it is about the wooden mask of an Asian demon on the writer&#39;s desk: &quot;I look with compassion at the swollen veins on my forehead, remarking: how hard it is to be evil.&quot;.
Films like The Hunting Party feature just such swollen heads, but they show how hard it is to be good.
This problem is not limited to the topic of war in the Balkans.
Recently this newspaper reported that all the Hollywood movies about Iraq were big failures.
There is only one thing to add to this: There has never been a good film about South Africa.
It is almost always true: When a star wanders through a crisis zone or walks through a minefield, a film like Rangoon with Patricia Arquette, Breaking Edge with Angelina Jolie or Blutdiamanten with Leonardo DiCaprio is created.
Maybe all the conflicts are just too close in time.
After all, decades had to pass before Hollywood could make a good film about the Holocaust - Schindler&#39;s List.
Much of the film apparently needs to mature - films that are now considered classic Vietnamese works - &quot;The Deer Hunter&quot;, &quot;Apocalypse&quot; or &quot;The Lead Vest&quot; - were by no means celebrated as masterpieces back then.
But perhaps today, when every mass murder appears on two screens at home, we know too much about the conflicts of this world.
Then screenwriters don&#39;t have the ability to flawlessly tell good stories.
After all, &quot;To Be or Not to Be&quot; or &quot;The Great Dictator&quot; became so good because Lubitsch and Chaplin did not yet know how terrible the Nazi regime really ruled.
Maybe you don&#39;t want to be good if you want to make good movies.
Maybe he needs to develop a sarcastically measured artistic view like the novelist Lawrence Norfolk.
When asked about the parallel between his historical novel &quot;Lemprière&#39;s Dictionary&quot; and &quot;The Balkan War&quot;, he stated: &quot;The similarity is only that some things never change.
