These are not Warhol boxes
Those who think of Sweden and wooden crates don&#39;t think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or yes?
Wooden crates currently produced in Sweden cast a dark shadow over the list of Warhol&#39;s works.
Most of his listed ninety-four Stockholm-type &quot;Brillo boxes&quot; are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper &quot;Expressen&quot; expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol&#39;s &quot;Brillo boxes&quot; from 1968 a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disillusionment; the six &quot;Brillo boxes&quot; donated to Moderna Museet in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - as are most of the other &quot;Brillo boxes&quot; of the Stockholm type that are in circulation on the international art market.
The preceding events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-blue-and-white design of Brillo soap powder paper boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 displayed - with Warhol&#39;s approval - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were supplied directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 for several wooden Brillo boxes to be made in Sweden, but they are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of that time are now talking about fifteen boxes, which rightly went down in art and auction history at the time as authorized originals - &quot;Andy Warhol&#39;s Brillo Boxes&quot; labeled Typ Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than 100,000 dollars.
The problem now is that legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that approximately one hundred crates were made and displayed in Sweden in 1968 and then left to him by Warhol.
In fact, 105 Hultén crates were made in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg as recently as 1990.
At that time, Warhol was already three years after his death.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator of the Moderna Museet, examined, in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood tops were painted with a base color and sanded, they were painted with white oil paint with a brush.
From the structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, it became clear that the paint was applied with a painter&#39;s roller directly to the plywood board without a previous primer - besides, it is an acrylic paint and not an oil paint.
&quot;These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol&#39;s official list of Brillo boxes,&quot; said Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: &quot;Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York comes to different conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to six to classify boxes from their exhibition collections as &quot;exhibition material - copies&quot;.
Back in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would look into these &quot;major allegations&quot; made in the case of the soap powder boxes.
But the organization still remains inexorably silent.
